segments.text: April 13.
We're continuing the conversation with Mr. Evans.
Yesterday, in error, I said it was the 11th of April, and it was the 12th.
This is Tuesday the 13th, and Mr. Evans is discussing Dean Kyle.
When you were a student, did Dean Kyle have a lot of influence on the campus?
Now, the
Football games were played on a field named Kyle Field.
When you were a student, were there stands for the football stadium?
Were there already some bleachers built?
Some kind of bleachers.
And there by the railroad track, how often did the trains go through?
Was it pretty often or once a day or what?
and y'all rode the train everywhere, when you were going to go back home, did you go through Houston?
San Antonio.
San Antonio, but from College Station, which direction did you go to get the train to?
Train.
Hempstead.
Oh, to Hempstead.
and then catch the San Antonio.
And did your family meet you in San Antonio?
I see.
To Pearsall.
And you said your father was growing onions at that time?
$8,000 for a crop.
And these were, you said, yellow Bermudas?
Was that a new variety of onion then?
Did you have brothers and sisters?
Two brothers.
Two brothers.
One sister.
One sister.
Did they go to college?
No.
You're the only?
Younger brother.
Younger brother.
Where did he go?
To A&M.
To A&M.
And did he major in agriculture also?
Dairy husband.
Dairy husband.
Ah.
And where did he live after he graduated?
In Brenham.
In Brenham.
In Brenham.
Let's see.
How often did you have a date when you were a student?
Didn't have many dates?
When y'all had a dance, was it held in Cebiza?
And you had the military ball,
Did y'all have the, did you have a senior dance?
What were the names, what kinds of dances, did they have any names?
Was the cotton ball held then?
That would be a big one later.
And the ring dance?
Now, the faculty all lived on the campus.
And were the faculty members all good to students?
Let's see.
And you said you went to class regularly.
Did you get sick ever while you were at A&M?
Well, if you had, you would have remembered, I bet.
Let's see.
Do you remember when you heard that the armistice had been signed?
Where were you?
Where?
You were in the dormitory?
How did you all learn about it?
In the newspaper or telegraph?
And what did you all do to celebrate?
Because I assume that you all expected that you'd be sent over to France if the war had not ended.
Now you were in an infantry outfit.
Did you all have a nickname?
You weren't the bad guys or tough guys or big bombers or anything like that?
Did many of your friends smoke then?
Did you smoke?
And if they did smoke, did they roll their own cigarettes?
Bull Durham, Prince Albert?
What about snuff or chewing tobacco?
Did some of the students dip snuff?
Did anybody try to keep beer or whiskey in their room?
And let's see, that was prohibition, so it wasn't legal to drink.
Was there a bootlegger anywhere near the campus?
Did you all have midnight yell practice then, before the game?
And silver taps?
And muster?
Where was muster held?
September 16.
Was it held on the steps of the YMCA?
Your final review when you were a senior, did your parents come for commencement and final review?
But you gave, oh, you weren't in the military as a senior?
But you told me yesterday you gave the valedictory address.
What did you wear?
Did you have a special new suit to wear?
When you were getting ready to leave the campus as a graduate, did you feel that A&M had prepared you well
to be out in the business world?
You already had a job.
Who helped you get that job?
And that was with the state 4-H.
So did A&M, did the people at A&M help graduates to get jobs?
Did you feel that A&M had prepared you well for that first job?
What is Aggie spirit?
Spirit you get after you're there four years.
Spirit you get after you're there four years.
Do you think that that spirit has been consistent down through the years?
Very consistent.
And what are the things that make Aggies proud?
I know.
And the media.
Celebrate.
Is that why?
Celebrate.
September 16.
Was that?
Mm-hmm.
As long as I was way back then.
What effect has A&M had on your life?
Yes, sir.
yes sir you've been you've been among the most if not the most generous person ever so you must have always been proud
Let's see, did Aggie rings in those days, did everybody wear an Aggie ring right after they graduated?
You just happened to have one on today.
There you go, there you go.
And do you remember what it cost?
Because now I think it's about $300, $12.
Did you have the money or did you need to borrow it?
Did y'all have a bonfire then before the Texas football game?
I did.
I did.
Do you remember where it was put?
Let's see.
When you were a student, were there any Jewish students at A&M then?
Were there any Mexican students?
And among you and your friends, did it matter that somebody was rich or poor?
Not a bit in the world.
I always thought the only thing that mattered was were they an Aggie or not.
Yeah, that's right.
Yeah, that's right.
Let's see.
Did you all have to polish Sully?
The statue of Lawrence Sullivan Ross, did you all polish it in those?
Let's see.
Was Prexy's moon up there?
Mr. Rutter used to talk about shooting that light out that was on top of the academic building.
And he said that when he was a student, they called it Prexy's Moon.
And that they would shoot at it.
Let's see.
I forgot to ask about Jack Williams, President Williams.
You worked with him.
What was your evaluation of him?
Fine.
I have always thought that nobody but Earl Rudder could have done what he did and nobody but Jack Williams could have done what he did immediately after.
That it was the two of them, do you agree with that?
The two of them did what needed to be done and laid the foundation
for A&M as it is today.
What do you remember most about Dr. Williams?
Very likable.
I remember a good sense of humor.

I worked very closely with Dr. Williams, and then with Mr. Rudder, I was the secretary of the Aspirations Committee and wrote that report for the faculty that recommended women, volunteer corps, racial integration, and higher admission requirements.
Yes.
Let's see.
Well then, I'm about through.
The last question I wanted to ask, what feelings do you have in your heart today about A&M?
Yes, sir.
If you were the
emperor or the king of politics and you could do anything for A&M that you wanted to do, what would you, are there any changes you'd make?
What would you do?
You'd move the railroad?
Anything else?
The only thing you, all right.
And the library, what do you hope the library will become?
Well, it's becoming a good one.
It certainly is.
And I'm glad it's in the middle of the campus.
And I'm glad that it is growing.
And it's doing that thanks to people like you.
It certainly is.
That's about all that I can think of to chat with you about.
Let me thank you so much, not only for myself, but for everybody that cares about A&M, for what you have meant to that school and will mean to A&M forever.
We are deeply indebted to you and deeply grateful to you for your generosity.
Thank you.
